{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011wG15GNtvMqLTZ9gLtDDHj","type":"tool_result","content":"1-# Usage\n2-\n3:Cloche runs containerized workflows for autonomous coding agents. You write a\n4-workflow graph in the `.cloche` DSL, point Cloche at a project directory, and it\n5-handles execution, retry logic, and status tracking.\n--\n34-\n35-The daemon listens on a Unix socket at `/tmp/cloche.sock` by default. It\n36:manages Docker containers, tracks run state in SQLite, and handles\n37:container cleanup. Containers are automatically removed after successful\n38:runs unless `--keep-container` is set. Failed runs always keep their\n39:container for debugging.\n40-\n41-To enable the web dashboard, set `CLOCHE_HTTP` (e.g.\n--\n54-This will:\n55-1. Write your prompt to `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt`\n56:2. Create a Docker container and copy your entire project into it (no bind mounts)\n57-3. Apply any override files from `.cloche/overrides/` on top\n58:4. Start the container, which runs `cloche-agent` to walk the workflow graph\n59-5. When the workflow finishes, the daemon extracts results to a `cloche/<run-id>` branch\n60-\n--\n88-```\n89-\n90:## Container Isolation Model\n91-\n92:Cloche provides **total filesystem isolation** between the host and container:\n93-\n94:- **Files in**: `docker cp` copies the entire project root into the container at\n95-  `/workspace/`. No bind mounts for project files. Override files from\n96:  `.cloche/overrides/` are then copied on top (e.g., a container-specific\n97-  `CLAUDE.md`). The `.git/` directory is included so agents have git context.\n98-- **Files out**: When the workflow completes, the daemon extracts results from\n99:  the container via `docker cp` into a git worktree and commits them to a\n100-  `cloche/<run-id>` branch.\n101-- **Auth mounts**: `~/.claude` and `~/.claude.json` are bind-mounted read-only\n102-  for Claude Code OAuth session reuse. `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` is passed as an\n103-  environment variable.\n104:- **Network**: Containers have network access (needed for API calls).\n105-\n106:Your project directory is never modified by the container. All changes live\n107-on the run branch until you explicitly merge them.\n108-\n--\n154-\n155-```\n156:cloche run --workflow <name> [--prompt \"...\"] [--title \"...\"] [--keep-container]\n157-```\n158-\n--\n162-| `--prompt \"...\"`, `-p` | Inline prompt written to `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt` and injected into agent steps. |\n163-| `--title \"...\"` | One-line summary of the work being done. Displayed in `cloche status`, `cloche list`, and the web dashboard. If omitted, the agent auto-generates a title from the first line of the prompt. |\n164:| `--keep-container` | Keep the Docker container even on success (default: remove on success). Failed runs always keep their container for debugging. |\n165-\n166-The current working directory is used as the project directory. It must be\n--\n171-with the project's `.cloche/Dockerfile`. If the Dockerfile has changed since\n172-the last build (tracked via a SHA-256 label on the image), the daemon rebuilds\n173:the image automatically before launching the container.\n174-\n175-### `cloche status`\n--\n181-```\n182-\n183:Output includes the run title (if set), run type (`host` or `container`), run state, active steps, and per-step results with timestamps.\n184-\n185-### `cloche list`\n--\n195-| `--all` | Show all runs, not just the last hour. |\n196-\n197:Columns: run ID, workflow name, type (`host` or `container`), title (truncated to 40 characters), state, container ID (if running), error message (if failed).\n198-\n199-### `cloche logs`\n--\n223-```\n224-\n225:Polls every 2 seconds. Exits 0 on success, 1 on failure or if the container\n226-dies unexpectedly.\n227-\n--\n234-```\n235-\n236:### `cloche delete`\n237-\n238:Delete a retained Docker container. Accepts either a Docker container name/ID\n239-or a Cloche run ID. If given a run ID, the daemon looks up the associated\n240:container.\n241-\n242-```\n243:cloche delete <container-or-run-id>\n244-```\n245-\n--\n344-\n345-Files in `.cloche/overrides/` are copied on top of `/workspace/` in the\n346:container. Use this for container-specific configuration:\n347-\n348-```\n349-.cloche/overrides/\n350:  CLAUDE.md              # Container-specific CLAUDE.md (replaces host version)\n351-```\n352-\n353:### 5. Make sure your project builds in the container\n354-\n355-The default Dockerfile generated by `cloche init` uses `cloche-base:latest` as its\n--\n487-```\n488-\n489:Or at the workflow level via a `container` block:\n490-\n491-```\n492-workflow \"develop\" {\n493:  container {\n494-    agent_command = \"gemini\"\n495-  }\n--\n501-\n502-Priority (highest to lowest): step-level `agent_command`, workflow-level\n503:`container { agent_command }`, `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` env var, default (`claude`).\n504-\n505-### Agent Fallback Chains\n--\n554-my-project/\n555-├── .cloche/\n556:│   ├── develop.cloche        # Container workflow definition\n557-│   ├── host.cloche           # Host orchestration workflow (runs on host)\n558:│   ├── Dockerfile            # Container image\n559-│   ├── config.toml           # Project configuration (orchestration, evolution)\n560-│   ├── prompts/\n--\n564-│   ├── scripts/\n565-│   │   └── prepare-prompt.sh # Host-side prompt generation script\n566:│   ├── overrides/            # Files copied on top of /workspace/ in container\n567:│   │   └── CLAUDE.md         # Container-specific CLAUDE.md (optional)\n568-│   └── <run-id>/             # Runtime state (gitignored)\n569-│       ├── prompt.txt        # User prompt (from --prompt flag)\n--\n586-| `CLOCHE_LISTEN` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Listen address (unix socket or TCP) |\n587-| `CLOCHE_DB` | `cloche.db` | SQLite database path |\n588:| `CLOCHE_RUNTIME` | `docker` | `docker` (container) or `local` (subprocess, for dev) |\n589-| `CLOCHE_IMAGE` | `cloche-agent:latest` | Default Docker image |\n590-| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | — | HTTP address for the web dashboard. Not started unless set. |\n591-| `CLOCHE_AGENT_PATH` | (auto-detected) | Path to `cloche-agent` binary (local runtime) |\n592-| `CLOCHE_LLM_COMMAND` | — | Command for LLM calls — evolution and merge conflict resolution (e.g. `claude`) |\n593:| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | — | Passed into Docker containers |\n594:| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_MOUNTS` | — | Extra bind mounts (comma-separated `host:container`) |\n595-| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` | — | Extra env vars (comma-separated `KEY=VALUE`) |\n596-"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"50dccf18-98cd-411d-b917-3226e2ea14f2","uuid":"857ff966-6ec8-4831-9270-26b8655a06ab","tool_use_result":{"mode":"content","numFiles":0,"filenames":[],"content":"1-# Usage\n2-\n3:Cloche runs containerized workflows for autonomous coding agents. You write a\n4-workflow graph in the `.cloche` DSL, point Cloche at a project directory, and it\n5-handles execution, retry logic, and status tracking.\n--\n34-\n35-The daemon listens on a Unix socket at `/tmp/cloche.sock` by default. It\n36:manages Docker containers, tracks run state in SQLite, and handles\n37:container cleanup. Containers are automatically removed after successful\n38:runs unless `--keep-container` is set. Failed runs always keep their\n39:container for debugging.\n40-\n41-To enable the web dashboard, set `CLOCHE_HTTP` (e.g.\n--\n54-This will:\n55-1. Write your prompt to `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt`\n56:2. Create a Docker container and copy your entire project into it (no bind mounts)\n57-3. Apply any override files from `.cloche/overrides/` on top\n58:4. Start the container, which runs `cloche-agent` to walk the workflow graph\n59-5. When the workflow finishes, the daemon extracts results to a `cloche/<run-id>` branch\n60-\n--\n88-```\n89-\n90:## Container Isolation Model\n91-\n92:Cloche provides **total filesystem isolation** between the host and container:\n93-\n94:- **Files in**: `docker cp` copies the entire project root into the containe